In Unity, a `BoxCollider` is an object that defines a collision region in the shape of a rectangular box. If you want to get the position of the opposite corners (i.e., the minimal and maximal corners) of the base and also considering the height of a `BoxCollider`, you can do this by taking into account the transform of the GameObject to which the collider is attached.

Here's a code snippet that demonstrates how to calculate the world positions of the opposite corners of a `BoxCollider`:

```csharp
using UnityEngine;

public class BoxColliderCorners : MonoBehaviour
{
    private BoxCollider boxCollider;

    void Start()
    {
        boxCollider = GetComponent<BoxCollider>();
        CalculateCorners();
    }

    void CalculateCorners()
    {
        if (boxCollider == null) return;

        Vector3 localCenter = boxCollider.center;
        Vector3 localExtents = boxCollider.size * 0.5f; // half the size in each direction

        // Get the local space corners of the box
        Vector3 localFrontBottomLeft = localCenter - localExtents;
        Vector3 localFrontTopRight = localCenter + localExtents;

        // Convert local space corners to world space by using the transform of the GameObject
        Vector3 worldFrontBottomLeft = boxCollider.transform.TransformPoint(localFrontBottomLeft);
        Vector3 worldFrontTopRight = boxCollider.transform.TransformPoint(localFrontTopRight);

        // To get the opposite corners of the base, we can simply ignore the 'y' component of the top right and bottom left
        Vector3 worldBaseFrontBottomLeft = new Vector3(worldFrontBottomLeft.x, worldFrontBottomLeft.y, worldFrontBottomLeft.z);
        Vector3 worldBaseFrontTopRight = new Vector3(worldFrontTopRight.x, worldFrontBottomLeft.y, worldFrontTopRight.z);

        Debug.Log("World Base Front Bottom Left: " + worldBaseFrontBottomLeft);
        Debug.Log("World Base Front Top Right: " + worldBaseFrontTopRight);

        Debug.Log("World Front Bottom Left: " + worldFrontBottomLeft);
        Debug.Log("World Front Top Right: " + worldFrontTopRight);
    }

    // Optionally, you could visualize the corners by drawing debug lines
    void OnDrawGizmos()
    {
        if (boxCollider != null)
        {
            Gizmos.color = Color.red;
            CalculateCorners();
        }
    }
}
```

Attach this script to the GameObject that has the `BoxCollider`. When run, it will calculate and log the positions of the opposite corners of the `BoxCollider` base, considering the height as well. You can see these positions in the console or visualize them with the `OnDrawGizmos` method by drawing lines or points in the Scene view.

Please note that the `localExtents` are calculated by taking half the size of the box collider (`boxCollider.size * 0.5f`) since the size property returns the full size of the box, and we want the extents from the center to the edges.

Always remember that the position and rotation of the `BoxCollider's` GameObject's transform influence these calculations. If your `BoxCollider` is on a GameObject that is a child of another transformed GameObject, the world space position will reflect this.

In Unity, you typically control animations using an `Animator` component and an `AnimatorController`. Here's a simple Unity C# script that you can attach to a GameObject to stop a currently playing animation and start a new one using the name of the animation state.

First, ensure your GameObject has an `Animator` component with an `AnimatorController` assigned. The `AnimatorController` should have states that correspond to the animations you want to play.

Here's the script:

```csharp
using UnityEngine;

public class AnimationController : MonoBehaviour
{
    private Animator animator;

    void Start()
    {
        animator = GetComponent<Animator>();
        if (animator == null)
        {
            Debug.LogError("Animator component not found on the GameObject.");
        }
    }

    // Call this method to change the animation by passing in the name of the new state
    public void ChangeAnimationState(string newState)
    {
        // Check if the Animator is not null and the newState is not an empty string
        if (animator != null && !string.IsNullOrEmpty(newState))
        {
            // Stop all running animations (this is optional and depends on your setup)
            animator.StopPlayback();

            // Play the new animation
            animator.Play(newState);
        }
    }
}
```

To use the script, attach it to the GameObject that has the `Animator` component, then call `ChangeAnimationState` with the name of the animation state you want to play.

For example:
```csharp
// Reference to the script on your GameObject
public AnimationController animationController;

// Function to call the transition between animations
public void SwitchAnimations()
{
    animationController.ChangeAnimationState("NewAnimationStateName");
}
```

Please note: The `Animator.StopPlayback()` command stops all currently playing animations that were started with `Animator.StartPlayback()`. If you want to stop a particular animation state and set a new one, you don't necessarily need to stop playback; you can just play the new state. The new animation state will replace the current if they are on the same layer. Also, ensure your animation states are properly set up in the Animator Controller, possibly with transitions if needed.

Restarting an animation in Unity with an `Animator` component involves first stopping the current animation and then replaying it from the beginning. Provided you're dealing with an `Animator` and not the legacy `Animation` component, here's a simple script that demonstrates how to restart an animation:

```csharp
using UnityEngine;

public class AnimationRestarter : MonoBehaviour
{
    private Animator animator;
    private string currentAnimationState;

    void Start()
    {
        animator = GetComponent<Animator>();
        if (animator == null)
        {
            Debug.LogError("Animator component not found on the GameObject.");
        }
    }

    // Call this method to restart the current animation
    public void RestartAnimation()
    {
        if (animator == null) return;

        // Optionally, if you want to force reset the animation
        animator.Play("StateName", -1, 0f);
        animator.Update(0f);

        // Or if you stored the current state name to a variable, it would be:
        // animator.Play(currentAnimationState, -1, 0f);
        // animator.Update(0f);

        // If you want to restart the animation that's currently playing
        AnimatorStateInfo currentStateInfo = animator.GetCurrentAnimatorStateInfo(0);
        animator.Play(currentStateInfo.fullPathHash, -1, 0f);
        animator.Update(0f);
    }
}
```

To use this script, attach it to the same GameObject that holds your `Animator` component. Call the `RestartAnimation` method from another script or via a Unity event when you need to restart the animation.

It's important to mention a couple of details about the above code:

- The `RestartAnimation` method uses `GetCurrentAnimatorStateInfo(0)` to get the current state of the default layer (layer index 0). If you need to restart an animation on a different layer, change the layer index parameter to the correct layer.

- The `animator.Play()` function takes the name or hash of the animation state, the layer index (use `-1` for the default layer), and a normalized time at which to start playback (use `0f` to start from the beginning).

- The `animator.Update(0f)` call is sometimes used after `animator.Play()` to force the Animator to update immediately to the new state, but it's optional and depends on the situation. If you call `animator.Play()` without `animator.Update(0f)`, the animation state will update during the next frame’s Animator update cycle, which might introduce a slight delay.

- If you are using a string to identify the state name, make sure the string matches the exact name used in the Animator Controller. It is also recommended for performance reasons to cache the hash using `Animator.StringToHash("StateName")` and use the hash instead of the string literal.

Please modify the method according to your needs and use it within the context of your Unity project.

Here's a Unity C# script that meets the requirements you outlined. The script will instantiate a fractured cube, apply explosion force to each piece, disable rigid bodies and colliders after 5 seconds, and make every piece disappear after 30 seconds:

```csharp
using UnityEngine;
using System.Collections;
using System.Collections.Generic;

public class CubeExploder : MonoBehaviour
{
    public GameObject fracturedCubePrefab; // Assign your fractured cube prefab here
    public Vector3 instantiatePosition = Vector3.zero;
    public float explosionForce = 100f;
    public float explosionRadius = 5f;
    public Vector3 explosionPosition = Vector3.zero;

    private List<GameObject> cubePieces;

    void Start()
    {
        // Instantiate the fractured cube
        GameObject fracturedCube = Instantiate(fracturedCubePrefab, instantiatePosition, Quaternion.identity);
        cubePieces = new List<GameObject>();
        // Apply explosion force to each child piece of the fractured cube
        foreach (Transform piece in fracturedCube.transform)
        {
            Rigidbody rb = piece.GetComponent<Rigidbody>();
            if (rb != null)
            {
                rb.AddExplosionForce(explosionForce, explosionPosition, explosionRadius);
                cubePieces.Add(piece.gameObject); // Add to the list for later reference
            }
        }

        // Start the disabling coroutine
        StartCoroutine(DisableRigidBodiesAndColliders());

        // Start the disappearance coroutine
        StartCoroutine(DisappearPieces());
    }

    IEnumerator DisableRigidBodiesAndColliders()
    {
        // Wait for 5 seconds before disabling
        yield return new WaitForSeconds(5f);

        // Disable all rigid bodies and colliders
        foreach (GameObject piece in cubePieces)
        {
            Rigidbody rb = piece.GetComponent<Rigidbody>();
            if (rb != null)
            {
                rb.isKinematic = true; // Disable rigid body by making it kinematic
            }
            Collider col = piece.GetComponent<Collider>();
            if (col != null)
            {
                col.enabled = false; // Disable collider
            }
        }
    }

    IEnumerator DisappearPieces()
    {
        // Wait for 30 seconds before making pieces disappear
        yield return new WaitForSeconds(30f);

        // Disable or destroy each piece
        foreach (GameObject piece in cubePieces)
        {
            // Option 1: Set the piece inactive
            // piece.SetActive(false);

            // Option 2: Destroy the piece
            Destroy(piece);
        }

        // Clear the list as all pieces are now destroyed or inactive
        cubePieces.Clear();
    }
}
```

Here's how to use this script in your Unity project:

1. Create a new C# script named `CubeExploder` and paste the above code into it.
2. Assign this script to an empty GameObject in your scene.
3. Create a prefab from your fractured cube model that you generated from Blender and ensure that each piece of the fractured model has a `Rigidbody` and `Collider` component.
4. Assign your fractured cube prefab to the `fracturedCubePrefab` field in the `CubeExploder` script via the Unity inspector.
5. Adjust the `explosionForce`, `explosionRadius`, and `explosionPosition` fields in the inspector if necessary.

After performing these steps, when you start your scene, this script will instantiate your fractured cube, apply the explosion forces, disable rigid bodies and colliders after 5 seconds, and destroy or deactivate all the pieces after 30 seconds. Adjust the timing and forces as needed for your specific game mechanics.

To activate an object according to different health thresholds, you can create a script that holds an array of objects and activates them based on the current health value. The following Unity C# script demonstrates how to handle such a situation:

```csharp
using UnityEngine;

public class HealthBasedActivator : MonoBehaviour
{
    [System.Serializable] // Makes it visible/editable in the Inspector
    public struct HealthThreshold
    {
        public int healthPercentage;
        public GameObject objectToActivate;
    }

    public HealthThreshold[] healthThresholds; // Array of health thresholds and associated objects
    private int lastActivatedIndex = -1; // Store the last activated threshold index
    private int maxHealth; // Store the max health for percentage calculations
    private int currentHealth;

    void Start()
    {
        maxHealth = 100; // Set your maximum health here
        currentHealth = maxHealth; // Assuming full health at start
    }

    // Call this function whenever health changes
    public void UpdateHealth(int newHealth)
    {
        currentHealth = newHealth;

        foreach (var threshold in healthThresholds)
        {
            // Calculate the percentage of current health relative to max health
            int healthPercentage = Mathf.RoundToInt(((float)newHealth / maxHealth) * 100);

            // Activate the object if the health drops below the threshold
            if (healthPercentage <= threshold.healthPercentage && threshold.objectToActivate)
            {
                // Deactivate previously activated object if necessary
                if (lastActivatedIndex >= 0 && lastActivatedIndex < healthThresholds.Length &&
                    healthThresholds[lastActivatedIndex].objectToActivate)
                {
                    healthThresholds[lastActivatedIndex].objectToActivate.SetActive(false);
                }

                // Activate current object and store index
                threshold.objectToActivate.SetActive(true);
                lastActivatedIndex = System.Array.IndexOf(healthThresholds, threshold);

                break; // Exit the loop since we only want one object active at a time
            }
        }
    }
}
```
To use this script:

1. Attach it to a GameObject in your scene.
2. Add the number of elements you want to have in the `healthThresholds` array through the Unity Inspector and assign the corresponding health percentage values and objects to each entry.
3. When the health of the character or object changes, call the `UpdateHealth` method with the new health value to automatically activate the appropriate object according to your specified thresholds.

Here's how you would call the `UpdateHealth` method:

```csharp
// Assuming 'this' is a component within the same GameObject as HealthBasedActivator
GetComponent<HealthBasedActivator>().UpdateHealth(newHealthValue);
```

Now, whenever you call `UpdateHealth` with a new health value, the script will check each threshold and activate the corresponding object based on the health percentage, making sure previous objects are deactivated.

Remember to set your objects in the array to inactive by default in the Unity Inspector. The script assumes that the health thresholds are set in descending order, so it activates objects for the highest threshold met by the current health and deactivates other objects. Adjust this script as necessary for your specific game logic and needs.

